tem><item><title><![CDATA[How four Moose released in 1904 ended up reshaping Newfoundland's forests forever]]></title><description>&lt;img border="0" hspace="10" align="left" style="margin-top:3px;margin-right:5px;" src="https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/photo/132604580.cms" /&gt;<![CDATA[A century after just four moose were released in Newfoundland to attract hunters, the introduced animals transformed the island's forests and wildlife management. Their population grew to nearly 200,000 before habitat damage triggered declines. A new management plan explains how science is now helping keep moose numbers in balance with forests, public safety and long-term ecosystem health.]]></description><link><![CDATA[https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/rest-of-world/in-1904-newfoundland-released-four-moose-to-attract-hunters-their-population-later-reached-200000-and-began-reshaping-the-islands-forests/articleshow/132604580.cms]]></link><guid><![CDATA[https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/rest-of-world/in-1904-newfoundland-released-four-moose-to-attract-hunters-their-population-later-reached-200000-and-began-reshaping-the-islands-forests/articleshow/132604580.cms]]></guid><pubDate>2026-07-24T18:44:00+05:30</pubDate><dc:creator xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/">TOI World Desk</dc:creator><enclosure type="image/jpeg" url="https://static.toiimg.com/photo/msid-132606009,imgsize-240600.cms"/></item><item><title><![CDATA[No good news for Indian B1/B2 visa applicants yet: $750 fast visa appointment pilot program starts in Mexico]]></title><description>&lt;img border="0" hspace="10" align="left" style="margin-top:3px;margin-right:5px;" src="https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/photo/132605933.cms" /&gt;<![CDATA[]]></description><link><![CDATA[https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us/no-good-news-for-indian-b1/b2-visa-applicants-yet-750-fast-visa-appointment-pilot-program-starts-in-mexico/articleshow/132605933.cms]]></link><guid><![CDATA[https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us/no-good-news-for-indian-b1/b2-visa-applicants-yet-750-fast-visa-appointment-pilot-program-starts-in-mexico/articleshow/132605933.cms]]></guid><pubDate>2026-07-24T18:09:40+05:30</pubDate><dc:creator xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/">TOI World Desk</dc:creator><enclosure type="image/jpeg" url="https://static.toiimg.com/photo/msid-132605997,imgsize-168080.cms"/></item><item><title><![CDATA[1,800-year-old Roman camp linked to Marcus Aurelius found in Slovakia]]></title><description>&lt;img border="0" hspace="10" align="left" style="margin-top:3px;margin-right:5px;" src="https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/photo/132603084.cms" /&gt;<![CDATA[Archaeologists have discovered an approximately 1,800-year-old Roman military camp in southwestern Slovakia that may have been used by Emperor Marcus Aurelius' army during the Marcomannic Wars. The site contains skeletons believed to be Roman soldiers buried in shallow graves, ditches and wells, along with weapons, armour, coins and military sandals. Researchers say the rare discovery could provide new insights into Roman military campaigns, although years of scientific analysis are needed to answer key questions about the soldiers' deaths and the camp's abandonment.]]></description><link><![CDATA[https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/rest-of-world/1800-year-old-roman-camp-linked-to-marcus-aurelius-found-in-slovakia-possible-soldiers-lay-in-pits-and-wells-with-armour-left-behind/articleshow/132603084.cms]]></link><guid><![CDATA[https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/rest-of-world/1800-year-old-roman-camp-linked-to-marcus-aurelius-found-in-slovakia-possible-soldiers-lay-in-pits-and-wells-with-armour-left-behind/articleshow/132603084.cms]]></guid><pubDate>2026-07-24T17:29:32+05:30</pubDate><dc:creator xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/">TOI World Desk</dc:creator><enclosure type="image/jpeg" url="https://static.toiimg.com/photo/msid-132603537,imgsize-148192.cms"/></item><item><title><![CDATA[Q